<p>TitleLeaf recommends the following <a href="/guides/ingestions/ftp-image-ingestion">image file specifications</a> when uploading images. To convert images in bulk using Adobe Photoshop, refer to the procedure below.</p>

<p>
  Setup: Download the Adobe Photoshop JPG settings from the
  <%= other_link 'shared Google Drive directory' %>
  and unzip. There should be two files contained therein:
  1) an actions file named <em>TitleLeaf.atn</em>;
  2) an image processor script named <em>TitleLeaf.xml</em>.
</p>

<ol>

  <li>
    <p>Load the actions file, <em>TitleLeaf.atn</em>, into Photoshop (Menu: Window &gt; Actions).</p>
    <p><%= cdn_image "photoshop-menu-actions.png", alt: "Photoshop: Load Actions" %></p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>Open the Image Processor window (Menu: File &gt; Scripts &gt; Image Processor...).</p>
    <p>
      <%= cdn_image "photoshop-menu-scripts.png", alt: "Photoshop: File menu, Scripts item" %>
      <%= cdn_image "photoshop-menu-image-processor.png", alt: "Photoshop: File menu, Image Processor item" %>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>Load the image processor script, <em>TitleLeaf.xml</em>, by clicking the <em>Load...</em> button.</p>
    <p><%= cdn_image "photoshop-image-processor.png", alt: "Photoshop: Load Actions..." %></p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>Select the source and target folders, verify that the action being run is <em>TitleLeaf 150 dpi</em>, then click the <em>Run</em> button.</p>
  </li>

</ol>
